<div id="review_3723925727" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3723925727" />
    <a title="Kat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100759205-kat"><img alt="Kat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643568808p2/100759205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3723925727?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kat" href="/user/show/100759205-kat">Kat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3723925727" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7236550753908214428">A reread. I wanted to finally get around to watching the show (mostly for Victoria Pedretti in S2, can’t lie). <br/>16 y/o me thought this book was way hotter shit than it actually is, and while there are some good things going on in <i>You</i>, it&apos;s definitely not as scandalous/edgy/impressive as I remember. <br/><br/>Caroline Kepnes does a fair job of creating an immersive, unlikeable narrator. I do think the writing gets stuck at times, trying to be as provocative as possible, hence all the erotic tangents. Howeve</span>
  <span id="freeText7236550753908214428" style="display:none">A reread. I wanted to finally get around to watching the show (mostly for Victoria Pedretti in S2, can’t lie). <br />16 y/o me thought this book was way hotter shit than it actually is, and while there are some good things going on in <i>You</i>, it's definitely not as scandalous/edgy/impressive as I remember. <br /><br />Caroline Kepnes does a fair job of creating an immersive, unlikeable narrator. I do think the writing gets stuck at times, trying to be as provocative as possible, hence all the erotic tangents. However, the driving force of Joe’s “good guy” act and the constant delusion surrounding his relationship with Beck allows for his inner monologue to not fall <i>too</i> far from its intended effect. The overall execution left me feeling a bit lukewarm the second time around, but the audiobook definitely kept me listening and gave me the refresher I needed. <br /><br />2.5 stars</span>
  <a data-text-id="7236550753908214428" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


